result.execSummary:
The defendant Kesley M Dvorak-Phillips was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Bail Jumping-Felony, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(b).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: Defendant must pay court costs and the cost of supervision while on supervision.  Defendant must submit a DNA sample as required by law if not previously provided.  Defendant must pay the DNA surcharge.   If supervision is revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant and in favor of restitution victims and governmental entities for the balance due.  Collections may include income assignment.

Defendant must obtain and maintain full time employment.
Defendant must obtain her high school diploma or it's equivalent during her period of supervision.

No alcohol or controlled substances.  No bars or taverns.  No drug paraphernalia  AODA and follow through with any recommendations including counseling.  Enroll in a treatment program and continue with it.  Random UAs as deemed appropriate by the agent.

Defendant must obey all rules and regulations while on supervision.
Defendant may work through reunification process with the child once she has established a stable residence.
Defendant may request expungement if she successfully completes probation.
Defendant must work towards obtaining a drivers license.
Firearms warning given.
Voting prohibited until sentence is complete and civil rights have been restored.
Appeal rights given.
